I'm a long-time Emacs user who's only recently begun dipping into Emacs/Elisp development. I used GNU Emacs originally, then XEmacs for a couple of years, but since Emacs21 was released, I use Emacs again. I started using CVS builds about a year ago for the Subversion support, and I rebuild at least every week or two. 

I love Unix and the administration thereof -- I once did it professionally. I've also been a mainframe programmer, network security engineer, a construction worker and a bookseller. I am currently a Housewife. I like to pretend that I'm not bad at cooking and photography. I work on weird projects that no one else cares about, mostly involving languages and archives of various sorts :)

I'm known as "mdxi" in #emacs, and in fact pretty much everywhere else on the internet. My homepage is at http://mdxi.collapsar.net/ and contains the requisite blog.

My Emacs code which has pages here on the wiki:

* OcrMode, my first major mode

I'm also responsible for the somewhat flammable essay WhyDoesElispSuck, which was/is intended much more as a prompt for discussion than a defense of elisp (and says so). I am glad it has generated some amount of thoughtful discourse.
